  "text": "O\u00f0log\u00f0 \u00de \u00fe 1\u00de times of optimum \u00f0F D2 G \u00de. Proof. Without loss of generality, let link L i;j be the link that has the maximum color ID, say g. To prove the theorem, we will show that g 2C 1;2 \u00c1 \u00f0log\u00f0 \u00de \u00fe 1\u00de \u00c1 . In the following, we prove it by contradiction and, for the sake of contradiction, assume that g > 2C 1;2 \u00c1 \u00f0log\u00f0 \u00de \u00fe 1\u00de \u00c1 . We first argue that for any 0 k log\u00f0 \u00de, there exists a link L i \u00f0k\u00de ;j \u00f0k\u00de such that r i \u00f0k\u00de ;j \u00f0k\u00de < r i;j =2 k and its color ID is not smaller than g \u00c0 2C 1;2 \u00c1 k \u00c1 . We prove this argument by induction on k. If k \u00bc 0, then the argument trivially holds. Assume for k p, the argument holds. From Theorem 15, by letting \u00bc 0 and \u00bc 2, ! \u00c1\u00f00; 2\u00de=\u00f02C 1;2 \u00de. In other words, the number of links, which interfere or are interfered by link L i \u00f0p\u00de ;j \u00f0p\u00de and whose radius is not smaller than r i \u00f0p\u00de ;j \u00f0p\u00de =2, is at most 2C 1;2 \u00c1 . Thus, there must exist a link L i \u00f0p\u00fe1\u00de ;j \u00f0p\u00fe1\u00de such that e ! \u00fe 1, which is a contradiction. Thus, g 2C 1;2 \u00c1 \u00f0log\u00f0 \u00de \u00fe 1\u00de \u00c1 . This finishes the proof. t u Algorithm 4 essentially is a First-Fit coloring method. It has been proved in [CITATION_1] that, any First-Fit coloring of an d-inductive graph with n nodes will produce a coloring using colors of, at most, O\u00f0d log n\u00de times of the optimum. Here, a graph G is d-inductive if we can number the vertices such that each node has at most d edges connected to the nodes with larger numbers. We essentially proved Notice that, in Algorithm 4, a node can start assigning timeslots to its incident links as long as it obtained the communication channel. Thus, the time complexity of this algorithm will be much close to the node coloring number of the communication graph G, in which two interfering nodes should be assigned different colors. Notice that, it was proved in [CITATION_2] that for disk graphs, the tight bound for approximation ratio for online coloring of disk graphs is minflog n; log g. Thus, we know that it is impossible to design distributed algorithm for link scheduling with better asymptotic approximation ratio when no any ordering are allowed among links.",
